SystemDesign Concepts

Consistency Models -> 
1. Strong Consistency, 
2. Casual Consistency(Causal consistency is slightly weaker than strong consistency. 
It ensures that if a read or write causally depends on a previous write, then any replica that serves the dependent operation 
will first apply that earlier write. In this way, the system preserves the correct cause-and-effect relationships between operations, 
without requiring full synchronization across all replicas.)
3. Eventual Consistency

Key primitives for coordination across services:-
1. Leader election
2. Distributed Locks -> pessimistic lock(Acquire lock first) , optimistic lock(perform action first and check later)
3. Consensus Protocol -> Paxos and Raft
4. Service Discovery

Apache ZooKeeper for coordination

CAP theorem -> In the event of a network partition, a distributed system can provide either consistency or availability, but not both simultaneously
PACELC -> If partition (P): If a partition (P) occurs, the system must choose between availability (A) and consistency (C). This is the original CAP theorem trade-off.
   A network failure forces a hard choice between staying online with potentially stale data or going offline to preserve data integrity.
   Else (E): In the absence of a partition, when the system is running normally, it must choose between latency (L) and consistency (C).

Amazon DynamoDB  -> PA/EL -> It chooses Availability during a Partition and Latency during normal operation (Else). 
It achieves this by replicating data asynchronously, which often provides eventual consistency.

Google Spanner, a globally distributed database, prioritizes strong consistency. It is a PC/EC system. It chooses Consistency during a Partition and Consistency during normal operation (Else). 
To achieve this, it uses atomic clocks and a protocol called Two-Phase Commit to ensure that all transactions are globally consistent.

Azure Cosmos DB is unique because it doesn’t force a single choice. Instead, it offers developers five different, well-defined consistency levels.

-> Achieving High Availability
1 Redundancy -> Redundancy can be physical (multiple zones, regions, servers) or logical (multiple service replicas running in containers or clusters).
  Redundancy Models:
  Active-Passive -> one component (the active component) handles all the traffic, while a duplicate component (the passive component) remains on standby. 
     The passive instance only becomes active if the primary one fails. This is also known as a failover setup. Eg:- Databases
  Active-Active -> All redundant components are active simultaneously, and a load balancer distributes traffic among them. 
     If one component fails, the load balancer simply redirects its traffic to the remaining healthy instances. This provides better resource utilization and faster recovery. 
     Eg:- Load Balanced Application servers

Split-Brain -> Under normal conditions, this leader directs operations so that all nodes agree on the system's state. When a network partition occurs, 
   some nodes may become isolated and lose communication with the leader. Each isolated group might assume the leader has failed and attempt to elect a new leader independently.
   This can result in a split-brain, where two leaders accept writes simultaneously, potentially causing severe data inconsistencies and corruption. 
   To prevent this, distributed systems use quorum-based consensus algorithms and fencing mechanisms. 
   Quorum algorithms ensure that a majority of nodes agree before a new leader can take control, which prevents conflicting operations during a partition.
